# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: virginia-general-assembly
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] The **161st Virginia General Assembly**, consisting of members who were elected in both the House election and Senate election in 2019, convened on January 8, 2020.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] It was the first time Democrats held both houses of the Virginia General Assembly and the governorship since the 147th General Assembly in 1993.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] A special session was called by Governor Ralph Northam for August 18, 2020 to make budget cuts and pass bills for criminal justice reform, racial justice, affordable housing and COVID-19 protections.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] The special session ended on November 9, 2020.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] After a shorter 30-day session occurred from January to February 2021, Northam called for another special session which lasted until March.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] After the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic, the State Capitol was closed to the public and sessions were re-located to alternative buildings.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] On November 9, 2019, Eileen Filler-Corn was nominated by the Democratic majority caucus for Speaker of the House of Delegates, and upon election by the House on January 8, she became the first woman and first Jew to be elected Speaker.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] Concurrently, Charniele Herring was elected as Majority Leader, making her the first woman and first African-American to serve as Majority Leader.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] In addition, Ghazala Hashmi became the first Muslim woman to be elected to the Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] Incumbent Danica Roem became the first transgender legislator to be re-elected to office in U.S. history.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] In total, the 161st General Assembly has the highest number of women elected to both bodies, with 30 in the House and 11 in the Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] Luke Torian to be the first African-American House Appropriations Chair in state history.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] This was the first time that an African-American delegate was selected to chair a House committee since William P.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] (D-Norfolk) chaired the Transportation Committee in 1998 and was co-chairman of the panel in 1998, according to House Clerk G.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] The Senate of Virginia has 10 Standing Committees and a Committee on Rules.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] Pre-filing of bills for the 2020 session began November 18, 2019.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] 828 bills were passed by the House by crossover day on February 12, 2020, an increase from the 603 bills passed under the Republican majority in the 2019 session.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] HJ 1, prefiled by Jennifer Carroll Foy, and SJ 1, filed by Jennifer McClellan, will make Virginia the 3rd state since 2017 and the 38th overall necessary to ratify the Equal Rights Amendment (counting the five that have since voted to rescind their ratifications).
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] Both bills were given initial approval, with SJ 1 being approved 28-12 in the Senate and HJ 1 being approved 59-41 in the House, and were passed by the other chamber on January 27.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] All Democrats and several Republicans in both chambers voted in favor of the resolutions.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] However, experts and advocates have acknowledged legal uncertainty about the consequences of Virginia's potential ratification, due to the expired deadlines and the five states' purported revocations.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/161st-virginia-general-assembly] A peaceful protest opposing gun control legislation occurred outside the Virginia State Capitol on January 20, 2020.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] The **163rd Virginia General Assembly**, consisting of members who were elected in both the House and Senate elections in 2023, convened on January 10, 2024.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] Both elections were the first to be held under maps for both houses of the Virginia General Assembly which were approved by the Virginia Redistricting Commission and the Supreme Court of Virginia in 2021, which were the first in Virginia history to not be drawn and approved by the legislature.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] Both elections resulted in Democrats winning majorities in both houses for the first time since 2021, with one-seat majorities in both chambers; it was the first time that Democrats won both houses of the legislature against an incumbent Republican governor since 1995.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] The 2024 session convened from January 10 to March 9, 2024.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] Following adjournment of the 2024 regular session on February 22, Governor Glenn Youngkin called a special session for May 13 for both completion of the 2024-2026 biennial budget and amendments to the 2023-2024 budget.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] Over Youngkin's objection, Democrats in both houses refused to adjourn the special session following completion of the budget, allowing the special session to *de jure* continue indefinitely until it was adjourned in the next term of the Assembly on January 15, 2026.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] The special session ran concurrently through the 2025 session, which ran from January 8 to February 22, 2025.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] On October 23, 2025, Speaker Don Scott called the General Assembly back to continue the special session on October 28 for the purpose of initiating a constitutional amendment allowing for mid-decade legislative redistricting of congressional districts.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] Delegate Don Scott, who was the minority leader of the House of Delegates in the previous General Assembly and won re-election, was nominated for speaker on November 11, 2023 by the incoming Democratic caucus.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] If voted into office, he would become the first House speaker of African descent in Virginia history, and the third person of African descent to preside over either house, after lieutenant governors Justin Fairfax and Winsome Sears in their roles as presidents of the State Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] Charniele Herring was elected Majority Leader and Kathy Tran as Caucus Chair.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] Republicans elected former speaker Todd Gilbert as Minority Leader (defeating a challenge from Terry Kilgore), Amanda Batten as Caucus Chair, and Michael Webert as Whip.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] In the Senate, due to the retirements of Democratic leader Dick Saslaw and Republican leader Tommy Norment, elections were held for leadership of both Senate caucuses.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] On November 15, 2023, the Democrats elected Scott Surovell to Senate Majority Leader, with Mamie Locke being re-elected Caucus Chair.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] Republicans elected Ryan McDougle to serve as Minority Leader, Mark Obenshain to serve as Caucus Chair, and Bill Stanley and Bryce Reeves as Whips.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/163rd-virginia-general-assembly] Constitutional amendments, under Virginia law, must be initiated by majorities in both houses in two consecutive legislatures before being sent to voters for approval.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The **164th Virginia General Assembly**, consisting of members who were elected to the Senate in 2023 and the House of Delegates in 2025, convened on January 14, 2026.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Democrats retained a majority in the Virginia Senate and expanded their majority in the House of Delegates, with Democratic former State Senator Ghazala Hashmi becoming the next Lieutenant Governor.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The 2026 session began on January 14 and is set to adjourn on March 14, 2026.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The 2024 special session that was called in the previous term of the Virginia General Assembly by Governor Glenn Youngkin briefly ran concurrently into the 2026 session until it was adjourned on January 15, 2026.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The leadership structure remained largely unchanged from the previous assembly, with Democrats maintaining control of both chambers, by 21-19 in the Senate, and 64-36 in the House.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] In the House of Delegates, Don Scott was re-elected as Speaker on January 14, 2026.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Committee assignments were updated at the start of the session, with key committees such as Appropriations, Finance, and Privileges and Elections reflecting Democratic priorities.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The regular session commenced on January 14, 2026, with key procedural resolutions adopted, including the schedule for bill introductions (deadline January 23, 2026) and crossover (February 17, 2026).
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] At the end of the regular session, on March 14, 2026, 3,646 bills had been introduced, with committees actively hearing legislation ahead of the crossover deadline.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Governor Abigail Spanberger delivered her first address to a joint session on January 19, emphasizing affordability, bipartisanship, and priorities such as healthcare costs, housing, and gun safety.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Governor Spanberger presented her budget proposal on December 17, 2025, focusing on affordability measures, including investments in education, healthcare, and housing.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Budget hearings were held on January 2, 2026.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The House Appropriations and Senate Finance and Appropriations committees are scheduled to report their budget proposals on "Budget Sunday," February 22, 2026, with each chamber expected to act on its budget by February 26.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] As of February 12, 2026, January general fund revenues were ahead of forecast by 2.9 percent, providing additional resources amid debates over spending priorities.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Controversies include Republican concerns over potential redirection of surpluses to partisan projects.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] After the regular session ended on March 14, 2026, without a budget bill passing, the General Assembly voted to convene for a special session on April 23, 2026, to continue negotiations.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The special session failed to produce a final bill, and, as of June 11, 2026, lawmakers are faced with a June 30th deadline to finalize the state's budget.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Negotiations remain stalled over several unresolved issues, including tax incentives for data centers.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] If the June 30th deadline passes, the state government will shut down, leading to uncertainty for agencies and local governments across Virginia.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The Democratic majorities advanced legislation aligned with campaign promises, including the "Affordable Virginia Agenda" focused on reducing costs in healthcare, housing, and energy.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] By February 9, 2026, more than half of these bills had passed either the House or Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Republicans criticized some measures as increasing taxes and burdens on the middle class.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] All four resolutions were passed by the House on January 14, 2026, and by the Senate on January 16, largely on party-line votes.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Governor Spanberger signed the bills on February 6, placing HJ4 on the April 21, 2026 Special Election ballot and the others on 2026 General Election on November 3, 2026.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Supporters argued the amendments protect essential rights, while opponents raised concerns over late-term abortions, human trafficking, parental consent, and potential gerrymandering in the redistricting measure.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Bills on solar siting reform (HB 359/SB 5) and public sector unionization (HB 582) also progressed.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] A bill to regulate cryptocurrency kiosks passed both chambers.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] The redistricting amendment sparked debate over potential gerrymandering and suspension of anti-gerrymandering laws in the budget.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Legislation on "claim sharks" targeting veterans drew criticism for empowering predatory companies.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] A bill (HB 359) requiring private religious schools to participate in state assessments and affirm gender identities raised religious freedom concerns.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/164th-virginia-general-assembly] Data center pollution bills advanced amid environmental debates.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] The **1961 United States state legislative elections** were held on November 7, 1961, for at least five state legislative chambers in at least three states.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats retained control of the New Jersey General Assembly and Republicans retained control of the New Jersey Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats retained control of the Kentucky House of Representatives and of the Kentucky Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Amelia Tucker, elected to the House, was the first Black woman to serve as a state legislator in Kentucky.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats retained control of the Virginia House of Delegates.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1961-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats won ninety-four of one hundred seats, a loss of two, Republicans won five, a gain of one, and an independent gained a seat.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] The **1998 United States state legislative elections** were held on November 3, 1998, alongside other elections.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Elections were held for 86 legislative chambers in 46 states.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Despite hopes of winning a majority of state legislatures for the first time since 1954 after a decade of steady gains, Republicans only flipped two chambers in the Midwest while losing control of six.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats flipped five of those, while the Washington House of Representatives becoming tied.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1998-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans had also forced a tie in the Virginia House of Delegates and gained control of the Virginia Senate early in the year in special elections.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] The **1999 United States state legislative elections** were held on November 2, 1999, alongside other elections.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Elections were held for 7 legislative chambers in four states.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Both chambers of the Northern Mariana Islands legislature were up.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of the Mississippi and Louisiana legislatures, while Republicans maintained control of the lower house in New Jersey and the upper house in Virginia.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans had won a 1997 special election to claim a 21-19 majority in the Virginia Senate after Democrat Charles L.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained this majority in 1999, which gave them their first-ever elected majority in history.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans flipped the Virginia House of Delegates, which was previously tied, resulting in the first-ever Republican majority.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Additionally, in the summer of 1999, a Democratic senator died in the New Hampshire Senate and was succeeded by a Republican in a special election, switching that chamber from Democratic control to tied.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Regularly scheduled elections were held in 7 of the 99 state legislative chambers in the United States.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Nationwide, regularly scheduled elections were held for 538 of the 7,383 legislative seats.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] This table only covers regularly scheduled elections; additional special elections took place concurrently with these regularly scheduled elections.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the Louisiana State Senate and the Louisiana House of Representatives were up for election to four-year terms in single-member districts.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of both chambers.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the Mississippi State Senate and the Mississippi House of Representatives were up for election to four-year terms in single-member districts.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of both houses.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the New Jersey General Assembly were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Assembly members were elected to two-year terms in two-member districts.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the Senate of Virginia and the Virginia House of Delegates were up for election in single-member districts.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Senators were elected to four-year terms, while delegates served terms of two years.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of the Senate and flipped the House of Delegates, which was previously tied.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All seats of the Northern Mariana Islands House of Representatives and half of the Northern Mariana Islands Senate are up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Senators are elected to four-year terms, and Representatives are elected to two-year terms.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/1999-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of both houses.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Elections to state legislatures were held on November 7, 2000, simultaneously with the 2000 United States presidential election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Elections were held for 86 legislative chambers in 44 states, simultaneous to those states' gubernatorial elections.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Election occurred in both chambers of each state's legislature, except for Alabama, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Virginia.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Michigan held elections for the lower house.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Six territorial chambers in four territories and the District of Columbia were up as well.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] These elections determined the redistricting process after the 2000 census.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats won control of the Colorado Senate for the first time since 1963.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Additionally, a coalition government replaced the Republican-controlled Arizona Senate, and the Democratic-controlled Maine Senate became tied.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Regularly scheduled elections were held in 86 of the 99 state legislative chambers in the United States.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Nationwide, regularly scheduled elections were held for 6,015 of the 7,383 legislative seats.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Many legislative chambers held elections for all seats, but some legislative chambers that use staggered elections held elections for only a portion of the total seats in the chamber.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] The chambers not up for election either hold regularly scheduled elections in odd-numbered years, or have four-year terms and hold all regularly scheduled elections in presidential midterm election years.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Note that this table only covers regularly scheduled elections; additional special elections took place concurrently with these regularly scheduled elections.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Alaska House of Representatives and half of the Alaska Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of both chambers.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Arizona Legislature were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of the House of Representatives and the Senate was replaced by a Republican-led coalition.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Arkansas House of Representatives and half of the Arkansas Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of both state legislative chambers.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the California House of Representatives and half of the California Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Colorado House of Representatives and half of the Colorado Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans held control of the House of Representatives, while Democrats won control of the Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Connecticut Legislature were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Delaware House of Representatives and half of the Delaware Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of the Senate while Republicans maintained control of the House.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Florida House of Representatives and half of the Florida Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of both state legislative chambers.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Georgia Legislature were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Hawaii House of Representatives and half of the Hawaii Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Idaho Legislature were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Illinois House of Representatives and 2/3rds of the Illinois Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of the House of Representatives and Republicans maintained control of the Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Indiana House of Representatives and half of the Indiana Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of the Senate and Democrats maintained control of the House of Representatives.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Iowa House of Representatives and half of the Iowa Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Kansas Senate and Kansas House of Representatives were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Kentucky House of Representatives and half of the Kentucky Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Maine Legislature were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of the House of Representatives, while the Senate became tied.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Massachusetts Legislature were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Michigan House of Representatives were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of the House.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Minnesota House of Representatives and Minnesota Senate were up.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of the House and Democrats maintained control of the Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Missouri House of Representatives and half of the Missouri Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans won control of the Senate, and Democrats maintained control of the House of Representatives.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Montana House of Representatives and half of the Montana Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans held control of both chambers.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Nebraska is the only U.S. state with a unicameral legislature; half of the seats of the Nebraska Legislature were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Nebraska is also unique in that its legislature is officially non-partisan and holds non-partisan elections, although the Democratic and Republican parties each endorse legislative candidates.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the Nevada House of Representatives and half of the Nevada Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Democrats maintained control of the House, while Republicans maintained control of the Senate.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the New Hampshire House of Representatives and the New Hampshire Senate were up for election.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] Republicans maintained control of the House of Representatives, and flipped control of the Senate from a tie.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the New Mexico Legislature were up for election; Democrats maintained control of both chambers.
[src:virginia-general-assembly/2000-united-states-state-legislative-elections] All of the seats of the New York Legislature were up for election.
